<br>
Their administrations were by and large competent, they both believed in multilateralism.  Reagan called the Soviets an evil empire yet negotiated arms treaties, and negotiated smiling with Gorbachev.  The &quot;downfall of communism&quot; was planned multilaterally and to be as painless as possible.  HW Bush put together an Arab coalition, a specific UN resolution and an exit strategy for the first Gulf War.  If he hadn't, Bumraz would likely still be there, his tour extensions and &quot;no-quit&quot; policy etc.  Clinton was a known multilateralist, I won't go into that.  <br>
<br>
What I remember most about Ronald Reagan, what I remember most of all, is that when those American marines died in Beirut, he said in his address that &quot;If responsibility exists for a policy mistake of this nature then it rightly rests with this office, with this President.&quot;  He took responsibility for his policy, whether it was good or bad- and he was humble about his role in the biggest change for good an American President.  Rest in peace Ronnie  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
All three of these Presidents that made America great and good again in the eyes of the world (2 Republican 1 Democrat) were greeted like heros when they traveled as statesmen.  For his achievements in the world Reagan was truly a hero.  Protestors follow Bush around everywhere he goes, more than I've seen.  Do I hate America because I can't stand a piece of shit deserter addressing veterans and comparing the sacrifices of WWII with a failed war of choice?  <br>
<br>
What have I said here after all Kura?  The Iraq policy was wrong, and is failing.  Torturing innocents is wrong and democracies shouldn't tolerate it.  Good government doesn't let this happen on its watch, and is held accountable when it is.  That's not hating America, just hatred of brutality, oppression and incompetent waste of life and treasure.  Last time I checked, America hated those things as much as I do.  Last time I checked, those are some of the justifications given for removing Saddam Hussein.  <br>
<br>
No, what I posted here isn't hatred of America.  You want to see hatred of America Kura, you go to the slums of Riyadh in Saudi Arabia and the Cairo Aq-Fayar ghettos in Egypt.  You go to the Palestinian refugee camps and see the results of a failed policy, where destitute poverty lives within eye's glance of the shining walls of a dictatorship of sheikhs fat on oil and American/British support.  There you will find hatred of America Kurakai, real and burning hatred.  You won't find a shred of hatred for America in my heart.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Despite what Fox news and other political neanderthals spout<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Fox news is Murdoch media.  Like all Murdoch media, from Fox, to Sky News in the UK, to Star News in the Middle East- Murdoch media without exception broadly supports the position of the governments in the countries that it covers.<br>
<br>
Even when those positions collide.  Members of Hamas' political wing are regularly interviewed on Star News Egypt, Israelis are described as &quot;Zionist murderers&quot; on Sudafi News, and America is called &quot;a global force of evil&quot; on Star News in Saudi Arabia(one of our allies- where incidentally Al-Jazeera is also popular).  If you want something I personally find disturbing yet hilarious, there is a show on Star News in Egypt(a country the US gives a billion dollars a year in aid to be friends with them)- called &quot;The Al-Massoud Factor&quot;.  He gives you the straight facts just like O'Reilly does!  Here's a quote from his show, translated from Arabic-<br>
<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>What is the difference between 10,000 civilians in Iraq, 6,000 in Afghanistan and the 3,000 Americans killed in America?  There isn't one my friends!  3,000 Americans killed in America by extremists, and 16,000 innocent Muslims killed in two countries by soldiers ordered by religious extremists on a crusade.  They even said it was a crusade.  Extremist militants attack America killing innocents then extremist Americans order the killing and torture of innocents in revenge.  You've heard what they say just like you here what bin Laden's tapes say- the broad message is the same &quot;Us Against Them&quot;- it is a hateful propaganda that they both believe.  <br>
<br>
Extremist militants run away like cowards after sending young men to blow themselves up.  They aren't accountable for their murders.  The American extremists in power hide like cowards behind the actions of their troops on their oil-profiteering pedestal of power- you and I know there isn't a real difference there.  If there was why is their Vice-President's oil company given a contract for Iraqi oil that no one had a chance to bid for?<br>
<br>
We know the score viewers, we've known it for years, just as we've known Sharon and Islamic Jihad have no difference with bin Laden and Bush- they're all murderers.  The worst part for me is that they never dirtied their hands with what they believed in themselves.  Bin Laden was a rich oil businessman, Bush was a coward who ran away from his army in Vietnam, the leaders of Islamic Jihad would never blow *themselves* up!&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Sanctimonious and insidious bullshit like that is what Murdoch media broadcasts in the Middle East- it's Fox News looking in the mirror.  So you'll forgive me Kura if I don't take at face value what Murdoch's media says in the US on Fox News when all it does is preach to the government and extremist position crowds in whatever country it's in.  Murdoch's stance as a businessman is expeditious and calculating- the calculation here is that Americans rarely if ever look for foreign sources of news, especially those with extreme viewpoints, the same goes for Middle Eastern viewers.  So it's relatively easy for the two extremist viewpoints to coexist in the same media organization, like two ships passing in the night.  <br>
<br>
Lastly Kura- I'm not on any side of any aisle.  I just think that torture and police state behavior is wrong and that competent democratic states/governments don't let it happen.  Torture of innocent civilians shouldn't be a partisan issue for god's sake, it is just WRONG.  Stop believing that and we might as well not be fighting terrorism.  If saying that torture is wrong, imprisonment without trial is wrong and that the Iraq policy was wrong is hating America in your eyes, then I'm saddened and astonished.  Especially since half of America does think the policy was wrong, and far more than half believe it's being mismanaged.  But I guess they all hate America to you Kura, they must do if they agree with me.<br>
