Now to Tomza-<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>First, I'll agree that Tar is very well read on the subject matter, but you attack my morals and place me in a certain American Stereotype <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
What stereotype am I placing you in?  I know of no American stereotype that equates with a brutal torturer.  Anyone with a vaguely German accent in a Gestapo coat being a torturer in a Hollywood film on the other hand...that *is* a stereotype <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> but I understand that some people who have been living their whole lives in a society where they are told what to do might not like the chaos that a democracy holds.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well the only problem with that line of argumentation is that the rule of law is not at all chaotic.  The rule of law is anything but chaos, it provides certainty and the bedrock upon which democracy is built.  In the Iraqi constitution like the American constitution, due process of law is imperative.<br>
<br>
What would you find more chaotic- soldiers sweeping residential areas and rounding people up, or a regulated system of due process law?  I find the latter more democratic and a lot less chaotic.  Again, Stalin, Chairman Mao, Pol Pot and every other tin pot dictator and brutal communist dictator sniggered at democracy for being so &quot;chaotic and unstable&quot;.  Indeed...I wonder where they all are now? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
The ironic thing is that democracy is incredibly stable- 90% of democracies that have been established naturally have survived.  Only where serious foreign intervention takes place (CIA assasination of Mossadeq in Iran or MI6 liquidation of Bashar Sulaiman) does democracy ever give way to authoritarian government.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You take out quotes and put words in my mouth, like saying how I support torture<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I never said you supported torture, I merely said you were indifferent enough about the subject to make me ill.  I may not be a slave owner or whip slaves for example, but if I invest my money or opinions in a company that would go bankrupt without the slave trade- I am still tolerant enough of it to let it happen and profit by it.  Tolerance of morally heinous actions doesn't mean you condone them, but it does mean you accept them with apathy.  Something I personally am unwilling to do.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I was iterating the ability to pick people up was right because it was wartime<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>but with the loss of liberties during wartime, I see it differently<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
See I think we have a misunderstanding here, I apologize for not clearing it up sooner.  You say in wartime, the war has been fought and done with.  There are no moving fronts, no axes of advance, no clearly defined battlefield, no organized battlegroups facing us.  This isn't war, but occupation and an insurgency challenging the legitimacy of that occupation.  In such a situation, suspending civil liberties only creates tension and atrocity- Northern Ireland, Cyprus and Israel-Palestine provide perfect examples of how counter-insurgency and brutality work at cross-purposes.  Heavy handed tactics of any kind simply provide fuel for the insurgency and rob the occupiers inch by inch of the moral high ground.<br>
<br>
If it was a battlefield situation, then I can see how innocent people might be briefly detained.  But these individuals were detained and tortured for months at a time, nearly a year in some cases.  Whatever it is they're supposed to have done, it hasn't been proven and the process isn't even remotely transparent.  That is dangerous and is a big part of the reason why the security situation is far from improving.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The statements I made were that things like that happen all the time and that even our own citizens fall into those cracks <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
It wasn't a crack but a huge gaping fucking hole.  US citizens fall through cracks in a well oiled and fundamentally fair (in most states) process of law.  The only process in Iraq is the say-so of occupying forces and appointed authority- nowhere near the same thing.  US citizens are answerable to each other, and all 3 branches of government- not to some foreign occupying army.  If you can appreciate the significant differences, and put yourself in the shoes of an Iraqi civilian without any way to challenge being detained or to prove your innocence- then perhaps you'd see what I'm getting at.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I meant it as being able to look into things with a lesser suspicion, instead of having to get a suponea (sp) from a judge in order to check the premises<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I'm not suggesting red tape to hamstring security measures.  What I am saying is that good street-level intelligence is a must.  Not just a random Iraqi pointing the finger at another- but reliable turned sources inside the insurgency.  Given the apalling lack of soldiers that understand local affairs or even know more than a few words of Arabic- it is impossible to gather the intelligence needed to arrest guilty parties reliably without due process.  Without the guarantee of good street intelligence, you're always going to get a majority of innocents by randomly sweeping a &quot;hostile&quot; neighborhood- and possibly create enough hostility for the teenage son of a prisoner murdered in custody to strap a bomb to himself.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>These things are still around... There is still racism, there are still sweat shops in some lesser developed countries(nearly like slavery), there are still militant prisions, there is still segregation(by choice) and cliques. Definitly not to the same extent as in the past<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Slavery as defined by the sale of human beings as property has been eradicated- the same is true of apartheid politics and politico-religious inquisition.  Their abolition didn't occur by people being &quot;sad&quot; about it, it happened by active engagement in a political process.  Tolerating injustice in the name of security has overthrown dozens of immoral principles and policies.  But it all begins with a clear stand against the wrongdoing- without a clear belief that it is wrong in any circumstance, then it is certain the practice won't change.<br>
<br>
Segregation by choice isn't apartheid, it's human ignorance, and you can't make ignorance illegal, else we'd have to arrest the whole of Lucid Vision and most of Sullon Zek.  The laborers in sweat shops aren't property, they are paid a wage and don't wear a slave collar.  They can also leave their job at any time, equating that with slavery is extremely misleading.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And yes, you are very ideological in your arguements, you base everything on &quot;natural laws&quot;, your morals and your type of justice<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I don't believe in natural law persay- as argued by HLA Hart the jurisprudential philosopher.  I favor the Ronald Dworkin view, that law is a reflection of society and its values.  Civilized values, values that the United States has always stood for, clearly declare torture of innocents as abhorrent and unconscienable.  If American civilians abroad were detained in prisons without trial and tortured, you can be sure their government should and would stand up for their rights.  Who stands up for the Iraqis?  They have no government, no legal recourse and no oversight on their detention- much the same as the 3 children at Guantanomo.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Not saying its wrong or anything, John Locke and many other people thought the same ways<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Locke hated the idea of natural law, and would likely have argued with HLA Hart extensively over his merits.  Locke was far more a subscriber to the legal precedents of common law which reflected society's values.  That was the nature of his &quot;social contract&quot;- based on the intrinsic values a society holds dear, not its morals.<br>
<br>
I am not being ideological when I say these are wrong- I am looking at the long chain of common law and international legal boundaries that clearly forbid it.  Boundaries that it has been US policy to respect, obey and attempt to spread across the world by persuasion.  Trying to impose such values by force inevitably means abandoning some of the most important ones along the way.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Plus earlier you even stated about how Nazi's were able to imprison anyone that opposed their war plans, well how do you think they got so far? People saw the warning signs coming, but they appeased him slowly until he grew<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You overlook the apathy of the German people in your statement.  You're acting as if the Nazi's progression in power base is the fault of nations that appeased them.  Where the real fault lies was in the apathy of the German people to the terrible state of their government.  Much like the apathy towards torture I've seen here, and the general apathy towards politics the majority of people reading this probably possess.  When people withdraw from politically engaging their government, things like the Nazi rise to power happen all too easily.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>you argue your ideology against theirs - you argue that if we stoop down to their level, we are no better than them <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I use that argument as a stepping stone if you read my posts carefully.  I say that if we stoop to their level or in that direction, that the moral justification for invading and then occupying that country is lessened.  When that justification diminishes, more Iraqis will ask themselves whether or not the occupation is worth it.  When if they are being ruled in a dictatorial fashion with no say in affairs or their own detention, there's a chance they'll wonder whether or not one of their own despots mightn't be better than the foreign variety of despotism.  <br>
<br>
The snippet you take from my post is somewhat dogmatic yes- but it forms the cornerstone of a clear policy argument.  That morally degrading our position threatens the success of the policy in a very serious way.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Anyway, I've read your points, and I know you wont change how you view things, on the other hand I might, since im still pretty impressionable and new to this kind of stuff<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
In the presence of a convincing arguments that engage and clash effectively with mine- I am more than willing to change my opinion.  <br>
<br>
But as you've already seen, more people are content to ignore what I say, refuse to read supporting evidence, refuse to read around or research the issue- or in other cases, simply call me an America-hater, an evil-doer, a dissenter or a coke-snorting liberal.  It's far easier to hurl insults or dissemble than it is to formulate convincing arguments.  However, when confronted by one I have been known to readily change my mind or at the very least re-evaluate and refine my position.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But, I do believe that some rules need to be bent to accomplish other things<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I am still not at all sure what you mean by this.  What exactly do you think is accomplished by bending these rules?  If anything significant has been accomplished I've yet to see evidence of it- perhaps you or someone else could provide it?  It's worth remembering that generations of people in a score of countries have died to help establish those rules.  I think it's wrong and expeditious to comply with them when convenient and discard them when they aren't.  That's what the worst tyrants of history did, being associated with that way of thinking undermines policy and plays right into the hands of the real terrorists.<br>
<br>
The crucial issue is this.  Whether or not you think bending the rules is justified or not, it has to be considered with another important consequence.  We are all fighting terrorism now.  The only way to defeat terrorism is to dry up popular support for it.  As long as there is popular support for terrorism, they'll have an enormous sea to swim in.  &quot;Bending the rules&quot; as you call it, will swell the popular support of terrorism and make it even harder if not impossible to apprehend people willingly shielded by a sympathetic populace.  If bending the rules means we threaten the strategic goals of global counterterrorism, is it then really worth bending those rules? <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
65 Archon<br>
